#observation(title: [Rheumatoid Factor — Not an ME/CFS Biomarker])[
Rheumatoid factor (RF), an IgM autoantibody targeting IgG Fc, is classically associated with rheumatoid arthritis but can be elevated in other autoimmune conditions (Sjögren's syndrome, SLE, mixed connective tissue disease) and chronic infections. Its relevance to ME/CFS has been examined but not supported by evidence:

The single direct study of RF in CFS found 11.8% RF positivity among n=51 patients @Hashimoto1992CFSRF, which falls within the general population RF background prevalence of 5--15% and lacked a control group (certainty 0.30). Subsequent studies confirm the absence of signal: a cohort study of post-parvovirus B19 CFS (n=140) found no autoantibody pattern — including RF — distinguished CFS from controls @Kerr2002ParvovirusB19CFS. The largest autoantibody profiling study in ME/CFS (n=172, 7,542 antigens, dual-platform proteomics) found no ME/CFS-specific autoantibody reactivity @Germain2025autoantibody. A 2024 systematic review concluded there is insufficient evidence to classify ME/CFS as an autoimmune disease @Batham2024MECFSAutoimmunity. Even in conditions where RF is known to be elevated — namely rheumatoid arthritis — RF seropositivity does not predict fatigue in large cohorts (n≈19,000 @Bergman2009FatigueInflammatoryRA, n=128 @Kozlowska2022FatigueRARF), confirming that RF is not mechanistically linked to fatigue even in its primary disease context.

*Limitations of the evidence:* The literature base for RF in ME/CFS is thin: only two studies directly measured RF in CFS patients, both predating modern ME/CFS case definitions and assay methods. No study has controlled for known RF-elevating confounders (age, chronic viral infection, occult autoimmune disease, smoking) in an ME/CFS population. Publication bias is possible: the three null findings (Kerr 2002, Germain 2025, Batham 2024) are consistent but underreported relative to broader autoantibody literature. (Origin: brainstorm)

*Clinical implication:* Elevated RF in a patient with suspected ME/CFS does not indicate ME/CFS autoimmunity — it warrants evaluation for occult primary autoimmune connective tissue disease. A subset of patients presenting with CFS-like symptoms may actually have undiagnosed Sjögren's syndrome; Sirois et al. found that 32% of CFS patients met Sjögren's diagnostic criteria upon systematic evaluation with Schirmer testing, salivary flow measurement, and serology @Sirois2001SjogrenCFS. However, Sjögren's fatigue is phenotypically distinct from ME/CFS fatigue @Kim2023SjogrenMECFS, supporting the importance of accurate differential diagnosis rather than attribution of autoimmune markers to ME/CFS pathophysiology.

*Certainty:* 0.65 (negative finding; replication across multiple independent studies; largest profiling study (Germain 2025, n=172) and systematic review (Batham 2024) agree on absence of signal).

*Replication status:* Negative — the absence of an ME/CFS-specific RF signal has been replicated across multiple studies and assay platforms.

] <obs:rf-not-mecfs-biomarker>
